results.notes:
Growing scattered in soil among leaf litter near the Mossy Brook Trail. Near Hamamelis virginiana, Crataegus sp., Quercus rubra, Quercus sect. Quercus, Acer rubra and Acer pensylvanicum. Caps finely appressed-scaly with a slightly greasy texture; convex; 53.9 to 76.7 mm wide and 13.2 to 16.0 mm tall. Gills adnexed and closely-spaced with 1 tier of lamellulae. Stems fibrous, dry and hollow; even to slighlty enlarged at the base; fragile; 64.5 to 74.8 mm long and 11.4 to 18.0 mm wide at the widest. Partial veil remnants present as a flimsy membranous annulus. Basal mycelium white and attached to thick white rhizomorphs. Cap and stem context white. Odor faintly potato-like. Taste like arugala but less spicy. Chrysocystidia present as pleurocystidia and cheilocystidia. Spores brown and smooth. Spore measurements: (5.2) 5.3 – 6.6 (7.9) × (3.4) 3.6 – 4.3 (4.8) µm, Q = (1.3) 1.4 – 1.6 (1.8); N = 30, Me = 5.9 × 4 µm; Qe = 1.5.

results.notes:
Collected in a small woodlot at the southeast corner of the intersection of Lisle Ave. and the CSX railroad. Growing abundantly in bare soil and in soil among moss on a ridge near Carya ovata, Quercus rubra, Quercus alba, Juglans nigra and Celtis occidentalis. Caps pure white or with a very faint pink flush; slimy and glabrous; 15.7 to 38.1 mm wide and 14.5 to 26.5 mm tall. Cap cuticles adnate. Gills deformed and sponge-like: white when young, becoming bright orange. Stems dry; 10.3 to 27.5 mm long and 4.2 to 16.2 mm wide. Context white and brittle. Cap and stem surfaces bruising brown. Strong fruity odor: like “ripe sweet plantains” developing a slight “sweet almond” odor after 2 days in a refrigerator (Django Grootmyers), “fruity and sour” (David Myers), and “mixture of chocolate and sour candy apple” (Matisse Grootmyers). Taste not distinctive. Many basidiocarps with rodent and/or insect damage. Not producing spore prints. Clamps absent. HYmenial cystidia smooth and irregularly fusiform: many with moniliform apices, few with branched apices. Hymenial cystidia measurements: (61.5) 62.1 – 76 (78.7) × (9.2) 10.1 – 13 (14.7) µm; Q = (4.7) 5.3 – 7.1 (7.5); N = 20; Me = 70 × 11.5 µm; Qe = 6.2. Basidia 4-sterigmate and clavate. Basidia measurements: (33.3) 33.8 – 39.9 (42.1) × (10.2) 11.7 – 13.5 (14.6) µm;Q = (2.4) 2.8 – 3.4 (3.8); N = 30; Me = 37.4 × 12.4 µm; Qe = 3. Spores amyloid with spines occasionally forming short ridges. Spore measurements: (7.9) 8.2 – 9.6 (11.2) × (6.7) 6.9 – 8.9 (9.7) µm; Q = 1 – 1.2 (1.3); N = 30; Me = 8.8 × 7.8 µm; Qe = 1.1.

results.notes:
This specimen was found in a grassy lawn surrounded by oak and pine trees in a partially shaded area. The cap, as you can see, is very distinctive with extreme cracking. The scent is not unique, just a mild mushroomy smell. It has a yummy nutty flavor that is slightly sweet. When cut in half the tubules slowly changed from yellow to a pale blue grey. After an hour they were a beige color tinged with some brown. The porous underside of the cap does not bruise, but with age changes from yellow to beige. It does not stain from pressure or cutting. This specimen is pretty dry. The black points on the cap seemed to turn blue over time, and it looked as if it might be due to a blue colored fungus.
I believe this may be a specimen of Leccinellum quercophilum.

results.notes:
This specimen was found on the floor of a mixed hardwood and pine forest, on the side of a trail. It close to oak and pine trees. results.notes:
Growing clustered in soil with Clavaria sp. near Abies balsamia, Alnus sp. Quercus sect. rubra, Ameliancher alnifolia, Acer saccharum and Prunus sp. Caps silky-fibrillose and conical; and 6.3 to 6.6 mm wide and 6.3 to 8.2 mm tall. Cap context olive. Gills adnexed and pale olive-brown. Veils and annuli absent. Stems fibrillose and hollow; 11.9 to 15. 9 mm long and 2.1 to 3.5 mm wide. Basal mycelium pale yellow. Stem context white. Odor not distinctive. Clamps absent. Pileipellis with brown intracellular pigment. Pleurocystidia absent or rare. Cheilocystidia forming a sterile band; hyaline; thin-walled; conical to fusiform to mucronate; rarely apically forked. Cheilocystidia measurements: (39.6) 42.2 – 64.1 (73.3) × (9.3) 10.6 – 18.8 (21.3) µm; Q = (2.7) 3.2 – 4 (5.9); N = 15, Me = 54.6 × 15.4 µm; Qe = 3.7. Basidia 4-sterigmate. Spores angular. results.notes:
Growing in a cluster situated inside a cavity in a massive decaying beech stump.

At first I thought these were Lentinus levis. Laid out a piece of cap to drop spores. The deposit seemed to occur very slowly; after 2.5 days I scoped what appeared to be a thinly white area on the slide. Found many living nematodes and nematode eggs. I included a few photos. Not sure if the presence of the nematodes could have any impact upon the ability of the mushroom to sporulate. But, when I scoped pieces of gill material I did not find any basidia.

What appear to be spores from the gill laid out are approximately 4.5-5.5 × 4-5, consistent with the expectation for H. tessulatus and definitely not L. levis.
Another consideration was Ossicaulis lignatilis. But for O. lignatilis the fruit bodies are too large and the context not resilient.
